llowing_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2014-09-11T10:43:12Z","updated_at":"2014-09-11T10:43:12Z","body":"I'm not too clear on scoping and verification, but loading data from within a view is probably your underlying bigger problem. Your views have too much responsibility if you're having them not only load data, but also be in charge of securing it. They should be rendering what they're handed. Have you considered loading the data needed to do rendering from the controller, or controller helper of some sort? If this is some kind of composite page where data being pulled is not exclusive related to the resource rendered, then perhaps a module (or method on application controller if appropriate) that let's the controller just load it's thing might help.\n","author_association":"NONE","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/varvet/pundit/issues/comments/55247469/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null,"event":"commented","actor":{"login":"jeffdeville","id":131664,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjEzMTY2NA==","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/131664?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville","html_url":"https://github.com/jeffdeville","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jeffdeville/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false}},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/varvet/pundit/issues/comments/55252856","html_url":"https://github.com/varvet/pundit/issues/207#issuecomment-55252856","issue_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/varvet/pundit/issues/207","id":55252856,"node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDU1MjUyODU2","user":{"login":"valscion","id":482561,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjQ4MjU2MQ==","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/482561?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/valscion","html_url":"https://github.com/valscion","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/valscion/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/valscion/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/valscion/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/valscion/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/valscion/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/valscion/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/valscion/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/valscion/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/valscion/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2014-09-11T11:48:02Z","updated_at":"2014-09-11T11:48:02Z","body":"Thanks for the response, @jeffdeville.\n\n> loading data from within a view is probably your underlying bigger problem\n\nYes, I agree. We tend to avoid that, but in this case we actually don't load the resources themselves but just their count, and the line itself reads quite nicely. And as it is ran based on layout and on nearly all, but not, I don't know where would be a better place to initialize an instance variable for it. Certainly not `ApplicationController`.\n\n> Have you considered loading the data needed to do rendering from the controller, or controller helper of some sort?\n\nYes, we have, but it wouldn't actually help this issue at all. The main painpoint is that we get a false sense of security when using the `verify_policy_scoped` function in all of our controllers, as it never raises an error due to `policy_scope` being used in some \"helper-ish\" place.\n\n> If this is some kind of composite page where data being pulled is not exclusive related to the resource rendered, then perhaps a module (or method on application controller if appropriate) that let's the controller just load it's thing might help.\n\nThat's good advice, thanks! This really does seem to belong more to the controller side, but as the size calculation need is layout-based, it might get a bit confusing.\n\nAll of the points you gave, however, won't help me in remedying this issue, which mainly points to `verify_policy_scoped` always setting the flag, never caring about what it is feeded in. We always have a need to load at least one scope besides the scope that is loaded in the `index` action of a particular collection, so we are never able to get the benefits of the `verify_policy_scoped`.\n","author_association":"NONE","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/varvet/pundit/issues/comments/55252856/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null,"event":"commented","actor":{"login":"valscion","id":482561,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjQ4MjU2MQ==","avatar